He is the second child in a family of 7 children (including 5 boys and 2 girls). His father was Tran Van Nhu, a native of Nam Dinh, and his mother, whose name is unknown, was originally from Ninh Binh. [1]
When he was baptized, he was given the name Peter. In 1840, he left his family with Father Tran Van Tieu as an auxiliary at Bach Bat parish. In 1845, he was admitted to the Vinh Tri minor seminary, changing his name to Tran Van Triem to avoid the same name as another seminarian. After graduating in 1850 and serving as a diacre at Trang Vinh Tri church, Ke Vinh land, Nam Dinh [2], he was sent to practice in a number of parishes until 1855 when he was admitted to the Ke Non Grand Seminary (Ha Nam), then run by Bishop Charles Hubert Jeantet (Vietnamese name Khiem), to continue learning more about philosophy. and Theology and Deacons.

In 1886, in response to the king of Ham Nghi, in Thanh Hoa, the Ba Dinh uprising led by Phạm Bên and Đinh Cong Tràng broke out. Father Chen Luc guided and assisted Hautefeuille in the capture of Ninh Binh. [9] In addition, he recruited 150 soldiers to help Hautefeuille protect security. [10]
